"1413":"1413","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","about 1445":"circa 1445","1509":"1509","Aft 1461":"na 1461","1527":"1527","Radwinter, Essex, England":"Radwinter, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tudeley-cum-Capel, Tonbridge, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Tudeley, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kirby le Soken, Essex, England":"Kirby le Soken, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Brenchley, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1420–13 July 1509":"1420–13 July 1509","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1420–1461":"1420–1461","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1404–1452":"1404–1452","1461":"1461","before 13 July 1509":"before 13 July 1509","1404":"1404","1446":"1446","13 July 1509":"13 July 1509","1413":"1413","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","about 1445":"about 1445","1509":"1509","Aft 1461":"after 1461","1527":"1527","Radwinter, Essex, England":"Radwinter, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Tudeley-cum-Capel, Tonbridge, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Tudeley, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kirby le Soken, Essex, England":"Kirby le Soken, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Brenchley, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Burr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>burre</i> ‘bur’ (a seed-case or flower-head with clinging prickles), used by Shakespeare to denote someone who sticks like a bur, a person difficult to ‘shake off’, a sense which may well be older.","German: topographic name from <i>Burr(e)</i> ‘mound, hill’, or in the south a variant of   Burrer  .","History: The American political leader Aaron Burr (1756–1836) was the son of a clergyman and academic, president of Princeton University. On his mother's side he was descended from the Puritan preacher Jonathan Edwards; on his father's from Jehu Burr, who emigrated from England to MA with John Winthrop (see   Winthrop  ) in 1630."],"variants":[{"name":"Burrer","meanings":["German:","from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>burren</i> ‘to buzz, complain’, probably applied as a nickname for a noisy or cantankerous person.","habitational name for someone from either of two places called Burren in Württemberg."]},{"name":"Burrs","meanings":["Altered form of English   Burr  , with the addition of excrescent <i>-s</i>, or perhaps of   Burrows  ."]}]},{"name":"Bures","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Czech and Slovak Milan, Jaroslav.","Czech and Slovak (<b>Bureš</b>): from a pet form of the old personal name   Burian  .","English (Essex): habitational name from Mount Bures (Essex) and adjacent Bures Saint Mary (Suffolk), both meaning ‘the cottages’, from Old English <i>būr</i>, plural <i>būras</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Burian","meanings":["Czech and Slovak (also <b>Burián</b>); Hungarian (<b>Burián</b>); Polish and Romanian: from <i>Burian, Burián</i>, an old personal name apparently composed of <i>bur</i> ‘peasant’, a word of German origin (see   Bauer   and   Bur  ), and the name   Jan   (Slovak <i>Ján</i>) ‘John’. In Czech, the name <i>Burian</i> or <i>Bur Jan</i> denotes Saint John, a Christian martyr who lived in the 4th century in Rome and is venerated together with Saint Paul. Compare German   Burhans   and the name below.","North German: variant of   Burhans  , formed with the personal name   Jan   ‘John’ in place of its cognate   Hans  ."]},{"name":"Buresh","meanings":["Americanized form of Czech and Slovak <b>Bureš</b> (see   Bures  ) and of their Germanized form <b>Buresch</b> (compare 2 below).","Americanized form of German (of Slavic origin) <b>Buresch</b>: from a short form of an Old Slavic personal name <i>Burislav</i> (composed of the elements <i>bur</i>, derived from <i>buriti se</i> ‘to stir up’ + <i>slav</i>, from <i>slava</i> ‘glory’). See also 1 above."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John William Burr Bures II, of Brenchley was born in 1420, in Tudeley, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, John of Brenchley Burr, was 21 and his mother, Lady Elizabeth De Ros Roos, was 16. He had at least 2 daughters with Lady Alice Walker. He died on 13 July 1509, in Brenchley, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1420–13 July 1509":"1420–13. juuli 1509","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1420–1461":"1420–1461","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1404–1452":"1404–1452","1461":"1461","before 13 July 1509":"enne 13. juulit 1509","1404":"1404","1446":"1446","13 July 1509":"13. juuli 1509","1413":"1413","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","about 1445":"